      [Moon emoji]
   =20
 =20

Last August, Ryan Cohen did a very funny joke. Cohen =E2=80=94=C2=A0founder=
 of online pet-food retailer Chewy, chairman of the board at GameStop Corp.=
 and general meme-stock influencer and activist=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0had spe=
nt about $121 million
  [1]
=C2=A0to=C2=A0buy about 9.8% of Bed Bath & Beyond Inc.=E2=80=99s stock in e=
arly 2022, and he sent Bed Bath=E2=80=99s board of directors  a letter advo=
cating some strategic changes. When his stake and activism were disclosed i=
n March, the stock shot up 34% in one day, closing at $21.71 per share. But=
 his strategy didn=E2=80=99t really work, Bed Bath kept deteriorating, and =
by August the stock was well below the $15 or so that Cohen had paid to buy=
 it.
But then, on the morning of Aug. 16, Cohen=C2=A0re-disclosed that he owned =
those shares. Nothing had really changed:=C2=A0He had not bought any more s=
tock since March, but since Bed Bath had done some (ill-advised!) stock buy=
backs in the interim, Cohen=E2=80=99s ownership had gone up to 11.8%, and h=
e filed an updated Schedule 13D disclosure form saying so. =E2=80=9CThere h=
ave been no transactions in securities of the Issuer by the Reporting Perso=
ns during the past sixty days,=E2=80=9D says the form, and =E2=80=9Cthis Am=
endment No. 2 was triggered solely due to a change in the number of outstan=
ding Shares of the Issuer.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Nobody read that, of course: Meme-stock investors saw that Ryan Cohen had d=
isclosed a larger stake in Bed Bath and, being meme-stock investors, decide=
d that that must be good news. The stock rallied, closing at $23.08 on Aug.=
 17, the day after his new filing.=C2=A0
And then he sold all his stock! Bwahahahahahaha! What a great trade. On Aug=
. 18,  Cohen disclosed that he had sold all of his Bed Bath stock on Aug. 1=
6 and 17, at an average price of almost $23 per share, for a profit of almo=
st $70 million. The stock fell to $11.03 the following day and kept falling=
; later Bed Bath did   some wild stock deals=C2=A0to stay afloat, which fur=
ther=C2=A0tanked the stock; ultimately it   filed for bankruptcy this April=
. Between last May and today, Bed Bath=E2=80=99s stock never closed above $=
15 (roughly Cohen=E2=80=99s purchase price), except on the four days around=
 his sales. He got out at the very top, and then the stock slid to bankrupt=
cy. Impeccable stuff.
Well, not impeccable. Some Bed Bath shareholders sued him for securities fr=
aud and insider trading. The theory is something like this:
=09Cohen had a loss on his Bed Bath position and wanted out.=09He decided t=
o use his meme-stock-influencer status to pump and dump the stock.=09Stage =
one of his plan was to tweet positive things about the stock, to remind mem=
e-stock investors =E2=80=9Coh, right, Ryan Cohen.=E2=80=9D=09Stage two of h=
is plan was to re-disclose his stake in the company, to further remind them=
 =E2=80=9Coh, right, Ryan Cohen.=E2=80=9D=09Stage three of his plan was to =
dump all the stock immediately.

This is a very weird theory! You could imagine that if Cohen was doing a pu=
mp-and-dump, he might tweet things like =E2=80=9CBed Bath=E2=80=99s earning=
s this quarter will be great=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cexcited to announce our n=
ew turnaround plan for Bed Bath=E2=80=9D or what have you. He did not. Inst=
ead, the shareholders object to tweets like=C2=A0this:


   =20

And, most of all,  this:


   =20

Get it? CNBC tweeted something about someone saying (correctly!) that Bed B=
ath=E2=80=99s stock was heading to $1, with an archive photo of a woman pus=
hing a shopping cart=C2=A0at a Bed Bath store. Cohen looked at the photo an=
d said =E2=80=9Cat least her cart is full,=E2=80=9D which honestly is not a=
 ringing endorsement of Bed Bath=E2=80=99s business strategy or future fina=
ncial performance. But =E2=80=94=C2=A0and this is the key part of the lawsu=
it =E2=80=94=C2=A0then he added =E2=80=A6=C2=A0well actually it just looks =
to me like a smiley face? But when I hover over it, Twitter tells me it is =
the =E2=80=9CFull moon with face=E2=80=9D emoji. Here is another rendering =
of it, from  a judge=E2=80=99s opinion on this lawsuit last week:


   =20

Sure, okay, a moon. The judge goes on (citations omitted):
Some online communities understand the smiley moon emoji to mean =E2=80=9Ct=
o the moon=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Ctake it to the moon.=E2=80=9D In other word=
s, according to Plaintiff, Cohen was telling his hundreds of thousands of f=
ollowers that Bed Bath=E2=80=99s stock was going up and that they should bu=
y or hold. They did so, sending the price soaring.
This was Aug. 12. The stock had rallied a bit when Cohen tweeted =E2=80=9Ca=
sk not what your company=E2=80=9D etc. (what company?!?), and then it ralli=
ed a lot more when he tweeted the moon emoji, and then it rallied even more=
 when he filed his amended Schedule 13D on Aug. 16, and then he sold it all=
.
Is that=C2=A0securities fraud? I mean! Cohen filed a  motion to dismiss the=
 lawsuit, and=C2=A0last Thursday a federal judge, Judge Trevor McFadden,  d=
enied it, saying that the moon emoji plus the updated 13D might in fact be =
securities fraud, and so the case can go forward to discovery and perhaps t=
rial.
I don=E2=80=99t want to overstate the importance of this: This is just a mo=
tion to dismiss, an early stage of the case, and the plaintiffs presumably =
won=E2=80=99t ultimately win unless they find some evidence that Cohen actu=
ally had a plan to pump and dump the stock. Still it strikes me as kind of =
a wild result? But I get it. My reaction was =E2=80=9Cwow this is a very fu=
nny joke that Cohen did,=E2=80=9D and as a general matter if you do somethi=
ng in securities markets that=C2=A0I=C2=A0think is a funny joke, many=C2=A0=
other people=C2=A0will think it is fraud. I have more of a sense of humor a=
bout securities markets stuff than some judges.
Still, wild! To me, the obvious problem with this case is that Cohen never =
said anything=C2=A0untrue.
  [2]
=C2=A0The judge disagrees, though, finding that Cohen made two public state=
ments that the shareholders could plausibly argue are not true. One is the =
moon tweet:

First, Bratya [the lead shareholder plaintiff] has plausibly alleged that t=
he moon tweet relayed that Cohen was telling his hundreds of thousands of f=
ollowers that Bed Bath=E2=80=99s stock was going up and that they should bu=
y or hold. In the meme stock =E2=80=9Csubculture,=E2=80=9D moon emojis are =
associated with the phrase =E2=80=9Cto the moon,=E2=80=9D which investors u=
se to indicate =E2=80=9Cthat a stock will rise.=E2=80=9D So meme stock inve=
stors conceivably understood Cohen=E2=80=99s tweet to mean that Cohen was c=
onfident in Bed Bath and that he was encouraging them to act. For example, =
one investor replied to Cohen =E2=80=9Cbuy $BBBY. Got it. Thanks.=E2=80=9D =
And Bratya plausibly alleges that Redditors gleaned the same message.
Second, that meaning is actionable. For one, it is plausibly material. That=
 is, there was a =E2=80=9Csubstantial likelihood that a reasonable investor=
 would consider it important.=E2=80=9D Investors appear to have relied on i=
t, driving Bed Bath=E2=80=99s stock price up in the following days. =E2=80=
=A6
Plus, that makes sense. Investors may have reasonably seen Cohen as an insi=
der sympathetic to the little guy=E2=80=99s cause: He interacted with his f=
ollowers on Twitter. He appeared to speak truth to power, criticizing =E2=
=80=9Ccompensation for the Corporate Power Brokers.=E2=80=9D He had a large=
 stake himself. He was =E2=80=9Cmaniacally focused on [Bed Bath=E2=80=99s] =
long-term.=E2=80=9D He had a public cooperation agreement with Bed Bath.=C2=
=A0He=C2=A0allegedly had access to material, nonpublic information.=C2=A0An=
d it seemed that he had helped oust Bed Bath=E2=80=99s former CEO. So it wa=
s not crazy for retail investors to follow his lead.
Nor is the tweet mere puffery. If Bratya had alleged only that the tweet ex=
pressed Cohen=E2=80=99s hope that the stock would rise, that would not be a=
ctionable. Likewise, if Bratya had alleged only that the tweet signaled Coh=
en=E2=80=99s excitement about Bed Bath, Bratya would have no claim. But Bra=
tya has plausibly alleged that Cohen=E2=80=99s tweet was more, an expert in=
sider=E2=80=99s direction to buy or hold.

What? The idea here is that the moon emoji represents not just optimism abo=
ut the=C2=A0stock, not =E2=80=9Cmere puffery,=E2=80=9D but that it represen=
ts =E2=80=9Can expert insider=E2=80=99s direction to buy or hold.=E2=80=9D =
That is a lot of weight to put on that little emoji. I wonder if some portf=
olio manager at a big hedge fund loaded up on Bed Bath stock after this twe=
et, and then the stock tanked and she got called into her boss=E2=80=99s of=
fice to explain herself, and she was like =E2=80=9Cno I had an expert insid=
er direction to buy this stock=E2=80=9D and the boss was like =E2=80=9Cyou =
did?=E2=80=9D and she was like =E2=80=9Cwell there=E2=80=99s this moon emoj=
i tweet.=E2=80=9D A moon emoji is not=C2=A0really =E2=80=9Can expert inside=
r=E2=80=99s direction to buy or hold.=E2=80=9D It is just sometimes, =E2=80=
=9Cin the meme stock =E2=80=98subculture,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D perceived that =
way.
The other supposed=C2=A0falsehood is the Schedule 13D, which accurately rep=
orted Cohen=E2=80=99s stock ownership at the time it was filed, but which q=
uickly became=C2=A0inaccurate
  [3]
:

Taking the Complaint as true, Cohen=E2=80=99s amended 13D was materially mi=
sleading as well. Investors filing 13Ds have a duty to disclose any solid p=
lans to sell their stock. =E2=80=A6
Bratya has plausibly alleged that Cohen had a definite plan to sell. For on=
e, the timing of Cohen=E2=80=99s sales suggests it. Cohen filed his 13D in =
the morning on August 16, 2022, and that very same day sold roughly $100 mi=
llion in Bed Bath shares. See Compl. =C2=B6 165. It is no stretch to infer =
that Cohen likely hatched that plan some time before that morning. More, Br=
atya has plausibly alleged that Cohen filed the 13D as part of a broader pl=
an to pump Bed Bath=E2=80=99s price so=C2=A0that he could dump his shares. =
=E2=80=A6
Despite the reporting requirement, Cohen did not mention his purported plan=
 to sell in his amended 13D.=C2=A0That was misleading. And it was material =
too: meme stock investors =E2=80=9Creacted positively to his filing,=E2=80=
=9D sending the stock price soaring =E2=80=9Cby over 70%=E2=80=9D that same=
 day.

Did he have a =E2=80=9Csolid=E2=80=9D plan to sell? The evidence, so far, i=
s just that he sold within hours after filing. Fine, but there is another o=
bvious interpretation:
Cohen offers a competing inference. He =E2=80=9Cdecided to exit his positio=
n when the price unexpectedly increased to a value that exceeded what he be=
lieved it was worth.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Plausible enough. But to accept this sto=
ry, the Court must view Cohen=E2=80=99s amended 13D as a lucky happenstance=
. In his telling, he had no concrete plans to sell on the morning of August=
 16. He then filed a 13D, and, as it had in the past, the price surged. The=
n (and only then) Cohen formed his plan to sell. That is a stretch.
Is it? He had bought this stock, it had gone down, he had a loss, he was le=
gally required to file an updated disclosure of his position that contained=
 no new information. He filed it, the stock shot up, he was suddenly sittin=
g on tens of millions of dollars of gains, and he very sensibly said =E2=80=
=9Cwell this is the best chance I=E2=80=99m gonna get=E2=80=9D and blew out=
 of the stock. He didn=E2=80=99t have a concrete plan to sell when he was s=
itting on a big loss, and he didn=E2=80=99t concoct a nefarious plan like =
=E2=80=9CI am going to file a 13D with no new information in it, which will=
 drive up the price, and then I=E2=80=99ll sell,=E2=80=9D because=C2=A0that=
 would be insane. Why would re-disclosing your existing stake, with no new =
information, cause the stock to shoot up? Except that it did, and he seized=
 the moment.
Back in the olden days, I learned that securities fraud meant lying about t=
hings that would be material to a=C2=A0=E2=80=9Creasonable investor.=E2=80=
=9D Everyone understands that if you go around saying =E2=80=9CBed Bath has=
 doubled sales this quarter=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CBed Bath has signed an agr=
eement to be bought by Amazon at $40 per share,=E2=80=9D and you are lying,=
 then that is fraud: You are saying things that aren=E2=80=99t true and tha=
t would be material to a reasonable investor thinking about the stock and t=
he company and its cash flows.
But in the world of meme stocks,=C2=A0there are no reasonable investors. Wh=
at matters is not cash flows or business plans but memes and influencers, a=
nd so the standards for fraud are =E2=80=A6=C2=A0perhaps different? In the =
world of meme stocks, if you are a meme-stock influencer, and you tweet a m=
oon emoji=C2=A0when you are in fact feeling pensive-face-emoji, then arguab=
ly you are lying, and arguably your misleading emoji is material to your me=
me-stock fans. They are not reasonable, necessarily, but they are the inves=
tors you=E2=80=99ve got, and if the stock doubles due to your emoji then I =
guess it was material.
  [4]
=C2=A0Similarly, if you accurately disclose your holding=C2=A0of a meme sto=
ck, and then for boring technical reasons you have to disclose it again, an=
d meme-stock investors misinterpret your new filing to mean that you are bu=
llish, and the stock shoots up with no news, then they have been=C2=A0misle=
d, and if you didn=E2=80=99t mislead them then who did? Well, they misled t=
hemselves, really. But if meme-stock investors are desperate to deceive the=
mselves, and you take advantage of their desire, maybe that=E2=80=99s fraud=
 too.

