The basic life of a coverage investment banker is that you travel around to=
 meet with your clients and talk to them about (1) what they want to do and=
 (2) what you want them to do. So you come in, you chat a bit about sports =
and their families, you ask =E2=80=9Cwhat=E2=80=99s new with you,=E2=80=9D =
they tell you about their business and financial concerns, and you listen i=
ntently and try to think of solutions to their problems, ideally but not ne=
cessarily solutions that involve paying your bank a big fee. Then you crack=
 open a pitchbook that your analysts prepared, saying, like, =E2=80=9Chere=
=E2=80=99s why you should do a leveraged recap=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Chere ar=
e four smaller competitors you could buy=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cthe convertib=
le bond market is hot and you could get great terms right now=E2=80=9D or w=
hatever.
Ideally, every so often, the client will say =E2=80=9Cyou know what, you=E2=
=80=99re right, we should buy that competitor, I=E2=80=99d never thought of=
 that before but it makes total sense,=E2=80=9D and she will hire you to do=
 the deal and pay you a big fee. That is part of why you brought the pitchb=
ook. But it=E2=80=99s not the only reason; your hit rate will be low. Mostl=
y you are trotting out these suggestions to improve your client relationshi=
p, to make your client think that you are smart and have=C2=A0a lot of idea=
s, that you spend=C2=A0time thinking about her problems and trying to find =
creative solutions, that you know everyone in her sector and can make deals=
 happen, and also that you have a big brain trust back at your bank who can=
 execute all sorts of transactions for her. And then when she=C2=A0does=C2=
=A0want to do a deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0maybe one you pitched, maybe not =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0she will call you and give you a fee, because of your loyalty and =
creativity and hard work and deep bench of subject-matter experts.
Meanwhile back at the bank you=C2=A0do=C2=A0have a lot of subject-matter ex=
perts, people who make all sorts of financial products for banking clients,=
 and=C2=A0they=C2=A0will be pitching=C2=A0you=C2=A0on things they want you =
to show your clients. =E2=80=9CWe have concocted a brand-new equity derivat=
ive that your corporate clients will love,=E2=80=9D the corporate-equity-de=
rivatives people
  [5]
 will tell you; =E2=80=9Ccan we come along=C2=A0to all your meetings this m=
onth?=E2=80=9D And you will think about the pros and cons.
Pros: Maybe the client will like the derivative trade, do it, and pay you a=
 big fee? Your hit rate is low, but you miss all the shots you don=E2=80=99=
t take. Or maybe the client will enjoy the derivative trade intellectually,=
 not do it, but think nice thoughts about you because of it. Also you might=
 as well keep the derivatives people happy, since you work with them, so if=
 they want to come to some meetings you might let them. Maybe they are fun =
to travel with.
Cons: Maybe the client will hate the derivative trade, be annoyed that you =
brought it to her, and think worse of you for it. Also you get like an hour=
 with the client, so you want to focus on what you think is interesting and=
 actionable, not what every random product person wants you to pitch. You h=
ave a=C2=A0relationship=C2=A0with the client; you are friendly; you have a =
running dialogue in which you listen to her concerns, think about them, and=
 come back with ideas to address them. =E2=80=9CHere=E2=80=99s a random der=
ivative our guys cooked up=E2=80=9D might just not fit in with that story. =
It=C2=A0might feel like an annoying impersonal distraction from your friend=
ship, an intrusion of=C2=A0commerce=C2=A0into your personal, trusted=C2=A0a=
dvisory relationship.
There is also I think something of a hierarchy of prestige, here, among the=
 coverage bankers. Pitching a merger? Always cool. Pitching a clever bond r=
efinancing? Sure. Pitching a weird tax trade that involves a ton of corpora=
te restructuring, that will take your tax people 45 minutes to explain, and=
 that no company has ever done before? Ehh, maybe, in exactly the right cir=
cumstances. Pitching =E2=80=9Cyou could save $25,000 a year by switching to=
 our bank=E2=80=99s cash management product at our new introductory rates=
=E2=80=9D? Feels like there might be more fun things you could talk about i=
n your limited time with the client.
Anyway here is  a Wall Street Journal story about how Barclays Plc=E2=80=99=
s corporate and investment bank has =E2=80=9Ca strategy to become a top fiv=
e player in as many lines of business as it can, if not investment banking =
overall,=E2=80=9D but has faced some struggles. It includes this complaint:

The investment bank=E2=80=99s new leaders, meanwhile, were internally touti=
ng the importance of diversifying how the bank makes money by focusing on m=
ore =E2=80=9Csticky,=E2=80=9D recurring revenues that can help balance out =
deal-making lulls.=C2=A0
Part of that goal involves becoming less reliant on one of Barclays=E2=80=
=99s specialties, leveraged finance=E2=80=94the business of making high-ris=
k loans, especially to fund mergers and acquisitions=E2=80=94and earn more =
fees from more lucrative offerings such as helping hedge funds execute trad=
es and large global corporate clients manage cash.
[Investment bank co-head Cathal] Deasy=E2=80=99s approach to making sure ba=
nkers aggressively pitch clients on the bank=E2=80=99s entire suite of serv=
ices=E2=80=94including more closely monitoring their interactions with clie=
nts=E2=80=94has rankled some, particularly those from Lehman who were accus=
tomed to autonomy.

Yes right if you are a senior investment banker from Lehman who enjoys pitc=
hing clients on mergers and leveraged finance deals, and now you have to fi=
ll out a weekly form asking how many times you have pitched Barclays=E2=80=
=99 cash-management services to your clients and what they said, you will b=
e rankled. Your client time is precious; you have an hour to discuss golf a=
nd mergers, and you do not want to waste it on cash management, even if tha=
t happens to be a better idea=C2=A0for the bank.

