Maybe the most important paper in economics is the one about how people som=
etimes give themselves painful electric=C2=A0shocks just because that is an=
 option that=E2=80=99s available to them:
For 15 minutes, the team left participants alone in a lab room in which the=
y could push a button and shock themselves if they wanted to. The results w=
ere startling: Even though all participants had previously stated that they=
 would pay money to avoid being shocked with electricity, 67% of men and 25=
% of women chose to inflict it on themselves rather than just sit there qui=
etly and think, the team reports online today in Science.
All of human culture is explained by that result.=C2=A0Anyway, three questi=
ons:
=09Would you let an artificial-intelligence mogul scan your irises with a c=
hrome=C2=A0orb for purposes of his own, if in exchange he gave you $50?=09W=
ould you let him do that, if instead of money he gave you some crypto token=
s that he made up and that have uncertain value?=09Would you let him do tha=
t,=C2=A0without=C2=A0the tokens?

When I put it like that it seems like the answer to at least the third=C2=
=A0question would be =E2=80=9Cno,=E2=80=9D but if you have ever met a human=
=C2=A0you know the answer is =E2=80=9Cyeah I guess whatever=E2=80=9D:

From Manhattan=E2=80=99s Oculus
  [6]
 building to a=C2=A0co-working space in Southern California, Americans are =
getting their irises scanned by a chrome=C2=A0orb=C2=A0that=C2=A0Sam Altman=
=C2=A0helped create.
Unlike the roughly 2 million people around the=C2=A0world who=E2=80=99ve co=
mpleted similar scans in exchange for payment, these US registrants=C2=A0ar=
en=E2=80=99t getting much of value from=C2=A0Worldcoin, the=C2=A0OpenAI=C2=
=A0chief executive's latest crypto project.
Drawn by a promotional blitz for an undertaking that has raised=C2=A0privac=
y=C2=A0and=C2=A0ethics=C2=A0concerns, a few orb pilgrims in New York, Los A=
ngeles and Miami hoped they'd get some crypto for their troubles, while oth=
ers were drawn by Altman himself.
Alex Chung, a user in Los Angeles, planned to make a YouTube video about hi=
s experience.
=E2=80=9CIf I scan my eyes, I can get 25 coins,=E2=80=9D he said. When he l=
earned that wasn=E2=80=99t true, he said he hoped to get the tokens =E2=80=
=9Csome day in the future.=E2=80=9D
Worldcoin's token launched on Monday at $1.70 and jumped as high as $3.58 b=
efore falling to around $2.18 on Friday, data compiled by CoinMarketCap sho=
wed. =E2=80=A6 Outside the US, Worldcoin hands out a few of its=C2=A0own cr=
ypto tokens, in increments worth about $50, to entice people to share their=
 biometric data.=C2=A0In the US, where Altman has said the crypto regulator=
y landscape is uncertain, the reasons for signing up are still mostly hypot=
hetical.
=E2=80=9CSam Altman is interesting =E2=80=94 he=E2=80=99s not only motivate=
d by money,=E2=80=9D said Alberto Simon, who came through a downtown Manhat=
tan store called the Canvas for a scan on Tuesday. =E2=80=9CI like random t=
ech stuff.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6
=E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t think I have any actual use for this right now,=E2=
=80=9D said Ben Deeb, who stopped by to offer up his irises in Los Angeles.=
 =E2=80=9CI just like trying out things. Plus, I=E2=80=99m a TV writer on s=
