<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Last August, Ryan Cohen did a very funny joke.=
 Cohen =E2=80=94=C2=A0founder of online pet-food retailer Chewy, chairman o=
f the board at GameStop Corp. and general meme-stock influencer and activis=
t=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0had spent about $121 million<a class=3D"footnote-inde=
x" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; displa=
y: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0to=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
32248570.290413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzg4NjE=
1OC8wMDAxMTkzODA1MjIwMDA0MjYvc2MxM2QxMzM1MTAwMl8wMzA3MjAyMi5odG0/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB99b58c3a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">buy about 9.8%</a> of Bed Bath &amp; Beyon=
d Inc.=E2=80=99s stock in early 2022, and he sent Bed Bath=E2=80=99s board =
of directors <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32248=
570.290413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzg4NjE1OC8w=
MDAxMTkzODA1MjIwMDA0MjYvZXg5OTF0bzEzZDEzMzUxMDAyXzAzMDcyMDIyLmh0bQ/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB80437f9f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> a letter</a> advocating some strategic =
changes. When his stake and activism were disclosed in March, the stock sho=
t up 34% in one day, closing at $21.71 per share. But his strategy didn=E2=
=80=99t really work, Bed Bath kept deteriorating, and by August the stock w=
as well below the $15 or so that Cohen had paid to buy it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But then, on the morning of Aug. 16, Cohen=C2=
=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32248570.290413=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzg4NjE1OC8wMDAxMTkzOD=
A1MjIwMDExOTkvZTYyMTg4Nl9zYzEzZGEtcmN2Lmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2283a=
ee3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"><em>re</em>-disclosed that he owned</a> those shares. Nothing =
had really changed:=C2=A0He had not bought any more stock since March, but =
since Bed Bath had done some (ill-advised!) stock buybacks in the interim, =
Cohen=E2=80=99s ownership had gone up to 11.8%, and he filed an updated Sch=
edule 13D disclosure form saying so. =E2=80=9CThere have been no transactio=
ns in securities of the Issuer by the Reporting Persons during the past six=
ty days,=E2=80=9D says the form, and =E2=80=9Cthis Amendment No. 2 was trig=
gered solely due to a change in the number of outstanding Shares of the Iss=
uer.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Nobody read that, of course: Meme-stock invest=
ors saw that Ryan Cohen had disclosed a larger stake in Bed Bath and, being=
 meme-stock investors, decided that that must be good news. The stock ralli=
ed, closing at $23.08 on Aug. 17, the day after his new filing.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then he sold all his stock! Bwahahahahahah=
a! What a great trade. On Aug. 18, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/32248570.290413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZG=
dhci9kYXRhLzg4NjE1OC8wMDAwOTIxODk1MjIwMDI0OTYvc2MxM2RhMzEzMzUxMDAyXzA4MTgyM=
DIyLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb6bbfd34" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Cohen disclosed</a> t=
hat he had sold all of his Bed Bath stock on Aug. 16 and 17, at an average =
price of almost $23 per share, for a profit of almost $70 million. The stoc=
k fell to $11.03 the following day and kept falling; later Bed Bath did <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32248570.290413/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMDcvYmVkLWJh=
dGgtYmV5b25kLXNvbGQtc29tZS1zdG9jaz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNzMxMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1=
fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA3MzEmdXRtX2=
NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8dd7f970" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  some=
 wild stock deals</a>=C2=A0to stay afloat, which further=C2=A0tanked the st=
ock; ultimately it <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/32248570.290413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLz=
IwMjMtMDQtMjQvYmVkLWJhdGgtbW92ZXMtaW50by10aGUtYmV5b25kP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA3MzEyM=
19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90=
ZXJtPTIzMDczMSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2b2=
bc86a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;">  filed for bankruptcy</a> this April. Between last May and =
today, Bed Bath=E2=80=99s stock never closed above $15 (roughly Cohen=E2=80=
=99s purchase price), except on the four days around his sales. He got out =
at the very top, and then the stock slid to bankruptcy. Impeccable stuff.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well, not <em>impeccable</em>. Some Bed Bath s=
hareholders sued him for securities fraud and insider trading. The theory i=
s something like this:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Cohen had a loss on his Bed Bath posi=
tion and wanted out.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">He decided to=
 use his meme-stock-influencer status to pump and dump the stock.</li>=09<l=
i style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Stage one of his plan was to tweet positive=
 things about the stock, to remind meme-stock investors =E2=80=9Coh, right,=
 Ryan Cohen.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Stage two of=
 his plan was to re-disclose his stake in the company, to further remind th=
em =E2=80=9Coh, right, Ryan Cohen.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bott=
om: 5px;">Stage three of his plan was to dump all the stock immediately.</l=
i>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is a very weird theory! You could imagine=
 that if Cohen was doing a pump-and-dump, he might tweet things like =E2=80=
=9CBed Bath=E2=80=99s earnings this quarter will be great=E2=80=9D or =E2=
=80=9Cexcited to announce our new turnaround plan for Bed Bath=E2=80=9D or =
what have you. He did not. Instead, the shareholders object to tweets like=
=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32248570.290=
413/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9yeWFuY29oZW4vc3RhdHVzLzE1NTU2NzYxOTMwNzE5MzU=
0ODk_bGFuZz1lbg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB88c7ea72" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">this</a>:</p>
<div class=3D"body-image" style=3D"margin: 20px 0px;">
<!--[if mso]>
<table width=3D"550"><tr><td><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://assets.bwbx.io/im=
ages/users/iqjWHBFdfxIU/ih0IuEtDaHxM/v0/-1x-1.png" width=3D"550" /></td></t=
r></table>
<div style=3D"display:none">
<![endif]--><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://assets.bwbx.io/images/users/iqjWHB=
FdfxIU/ih0IuEtDaHxM/v0/-1x-1.png" style=3D"max-width: 550px; display: block=
; width: 100%; margin-top: 20px;" /><!--[if mso]>
</div>
<![endif]-->
</div><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And, most of all, <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32248570.290413/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNv=
bS9yeWFuY29oZW4vc3RhdHVzLzE1NTgxMDE1NDE0NTM3OTUzMjk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cB9948f312" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;"> this</a>:</p>
<div class=3D"body-image" style=3D"margin: 20px 0px;">
<!--[if mso]>
<table width=3D"550"><tr><td><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://assets.bwbx.io/im=
ages/users/iqjWHBFdfxIU/ihJJd31xtIGo/v0/-1x-1.png" width=3D"550" /></td></t=
r></table>
<div style=3D"display:none">
<![endif]--><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://assets.bwbx.io/images/users/iqjWHB=
FdfxIU/ihJJd31xtIGo/v0/-1x-1.png" style=3D"max-width: 550px; display: block=
; width: 100%; margin-top: 20px;" /><!--[if mso]>
</div>
<![endif]-->
</div><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Get it? CNBC tweeted something about som=
eone saying (correctly!) that Bed Bath=E2=80=99s stock was heading to $1, w=
ith an archive photo of a woman pushing a shopping cart=C2=A0at a Bed Bath =
store. Cohen looked at the photo and said =E2=80=9Cat least her cart is ful=
l,=E2=80=9D which honestly is not a ringing endorsement of Bed Bath=E2=80=
=99s business strategy or future financial performance. But =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
and this is the key part of the lawsuit =E2=80=94=C2=A0then he added =E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0well actually it just looks to me like a smiley face? But when I h=
over over it, Twitter tells me it is the =E2=80=9CFull moon with face=E2=80=
=9D emoji. Here is another rendering of it, from <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32248570.290413/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5p=
by9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JJa3F3b0NPbEJPZy92MA/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cB4d5e81fc" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;"> a judge=E2=80=99s opinion on this lawsuit l=
ast week</a>:</p>
<div class=3D"body-image" style=3D"margin: 20px 0px;">
<!--[if mso]>
<table width=3D"550"><tr><td><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://assets.bwbx.io/im=
ages/users/iqjWHBFdfxIU/ib_t0if4On3I/v0/-1x-1.png" width=3D"550" /></td></t=
r></table>
<div style=3D"display:none">
<![endif]--><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://assets.bwbx.io/images/users/iqjWHB=
FdfxIU/ib_t0if4On3I/v0/-1x-1.png" style=3D"max-width: 550px; display: block=
; width: 100%; margin-top: 20px;" /><!--[if mso]>
</div>
<![endif]-->
</div><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sure, okay, a moon. The judge goes on (c=
itations omitted):</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some online communities understand=
 the smiley moon emoji to mean =E2=80=9Cto the moon=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cta=
ke it to the moon.=E2=80=9D In other words, according to Plaintiff, Cohen w=
as telling his hundreds of thousands of followers that Bed Bath=E2=80=99s s=
tock was going up and that they should buy or hold. They did so, sending th=
e price soaring.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This was Aug. 12. The stock had rallied a bit =
when Cohen tweeted =E2=80=9Cask not what your company=E2=80=9D etc. (what c=
ompany?!?), and then it rallied a lot more when he tweeted the moon emoji, =
and then it rallied even more when he filed his amended Schedule 13D on Aug=
. 16, and then he sold it all.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Is that=C2=A0<em>securities fraud</em><em>? </=
em>I mean! Cohen filed a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com=
/click/32248570.290413/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMv=
aXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3J5d2JRUlZPOUhlZy92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB60cb5887" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;"> motion to dismiss</a> the lawsuit, and=C2=A0last Thursday a federal=
 judge, Judge Trevor McFadden, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/32248570.290413/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdX=
NlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JJa3F3b0NPbEJPZy92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC4d5e8=
1fc" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> denied it</a>, saying that the moon emoji plus the updated 13=
D might in fact be securities fraud, and so the case can go forward to disc=
overy and perhaps trial.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t want to overstate the importan=
ce of this: This is just a motion to dismiss, an early stage of the case, a=
nd the plaintiffs presumably won=E2=80=99t ultimately win unless they find =
some evidence that Cohen actually had a plan to pump and dump the stock. St=
ill it strikes me as kind of a wild result? But I get it. My reaction was =
=E2=80=9Cwow this is a very funny joke that Cohen did,=E2=80=9D and as a ge=
neral matter if you do something in securities markets that=C2=A0<em>I=C2=
=A0</em>think is a funny joke, many=C2=A0<em>other people=C2=A0</em>will th=
ink it is fraud. I have more of a sense of humor about securities markets s=
tuff than some judges.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still, wild! To me, the obvious problem with t=
his case is that Cohen never said anything=C2=A0<em>untrue</em>.<a class=3D=
"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !imp=
ortant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0The judge disagrees, though, finding that Cohen made two public s=
tatements that the shareholders could plausibly argue are not true. One is =
the moon tweet:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">First, Bratya [the lead shareholder plaintiff]=
 has plausibly alleged that the moon tweet relayed that Cohen was telling h=
is hundreds of thousands of followers that Bed Bath=E2=80=99s stock was goi=
ng up and that they should buy or hold. In the meme stock =E2=80=9Csubcultu=
re,=E2=80=9D moon emojis are associated with the phrase =E2=80=9Cto the moo=
n,=E2=80=9D which investors use to indicate =E2=80=9Cthat a stock will rise=
.=E2=80=9D So meme stock investors conceivably understood Cohen=E2=80=99s t=
weet to mean that Cohen was confident in Bed Bath and that he was encouragi=
ng them to act. For example, one investor replied to Cohen =E2=80=9Cbuy $BB=
BY. Got it. Thanks.=E2=80=9D And Bratya plausibly alleges that Redditors gl=
eaned the same message.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Second, that meaning is actionable. For one, i=
t is plausibly material. That is, there was a =E2=80=9Csubstantial likeliho=
od that a reasonable investor would consider it important.=E2=80=9D Investo=
rs appear to have relied on it, driving Bed Bath=E2=80=99s stock price up i=
n the following days. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Plus, that makes sense. Investors may have rea=
sonably seen Cohen as an insider sympathetic to the little guy=E2=80=99s ca=
use: He interacted with his followers on Twitter. He appeared to speak trut=
h to power, criticizing =E2=80=9Ccompensation for the Corporate Power Broke=
rs.=E2=80=9D He had a large stake himself. He was =E2=80=9Cmaniacally focus=
ed on [Bed Bath=E2=80=99s] long-term.=E2=80=9D He had a public cooperation =
agreement with Bed Bath.=C2=A0He=C2=A0allegedly had access to material, non=
public information.=C2=A0And it seemed that he had helped oust Bed Bath=E2=
=80=99s former CEO. So it was not crazy for retail investors to follow his =
lead.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Nor is the tweet mere puffery. If Bratya had a=
lleged only that the tweet expressed Cohen=E2=80=99s hope that the stock wo=
uld rise, that would not be actionable. Likewise, if Bratya had alleged onl=
y that the tweet signaled Cohen=E2=80=99s excitement about Bed Bath, Bratya=
 would have no claim. But Bratya has plausibly alleged that Cohen=E2=80=99s=
 tweet was more, an expert insider=E2=80=99s direction to buy or hold.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What? The idea here is that the moon emoji rep=
resents not just optimism about the=C2=A0stock, not =E2=80=9Cmere puffery,=
=E2=80=9D but that it represents =E2=80=9Can expert insider=E2=80=99s direc=
tion to buy or hold.=E2=80=9D That is a lot of weight to put on that little=
 emoji. I wonder if some portfolio manager at a big hedge fund loaded up on=
 Bed Bath stock after this tweet, and then the stock tanked and she got cal=
led into her boss=E2=80=99s office to explain herself, and she was like =E2=
=80=9Cno I had an expert insider direction to buy this stock=E2=80=9D and t=
he boss was like =E2=80=9Cyou did?=E2=80=9D and she was like =E2=80=9Cwell =
there=E2=80=99s this moon emoji tweet.=E2=80=9D A moon emoji is not=C2=A0<e=
m>really</em> =E2=80=9Can expert insider=E2=80=99s direction to buy or hold=
.=E2=80=9D It is just sometimes, =E2=80=9Cin the meme stock =E2=80=98subcul=
ture,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D <em>perceived </em>that way.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other supposed=C2=A0falsehood is the Sched=
ule 13D, which accurately reported Cohen=E2=80=99s stock ownership at the t=
ime it was filed, but which quickly <em>became=C2=A0</em>inaccurate<a class=
=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !=
important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Taking the Complaint as true, Cohen=E2=80=99s =
amended 13D was materially misleading as well. Investors filing 13Ds have a=
 duty to disclose any solid plans to sell their stock. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bratya has plausibly alleged that Cohen had a =
definite plan to sell. For one, the timing of Cohen=E2=80=99s sales suggest=
s it. Cohen filed his 13D in the morning on August 16, 2022, and that very =
same day sold roughly $100 million in Bed Bath shares. See Compl. =C2=B6 16=
5. It is no stretch to infer that Cohen likely hatched that plan some time =
before that morning. More, Bratya has plausibly alleged that Cohen filed th=
e 13D as part of a broader plan to pump Bed Bath=E2=80=99s price so=C2=A0th=
at he could dump his shares. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Despite the reporting requirement, Cohen did n=
ot mention his purported plan to sell in his amended 13D.=C2=A0That was mis=
leading. And it was material too: meme stock investors =E2=80=9Creacted pos=
itively to his filing,=E2=80=9D sending the stock price soaring =E2=80=9Cby=
 over 70%=E2=80=9D that same day.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Did he have a =E2=80=9Csolid=E2=80=9D plan to =
sell? The evidence, so far, is just that he sold within hours after filing.=
 Fine, but there is another obvious interpretation:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Cohen offers a competing inference=
. He =E2=80=9Cdecided to exit his position when the price unexpectedly incr=
eased to a value that exceeded what he believed it was worth.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0Plausible enough. But to accept this story, the Court must view Cohen=E2=
=80=99s amended 13D as a lucky happenstance. In his telling, he had no conc=
rete plans to sell on the morning of August 16. He then filed a 13D, and, a=
s it had in the past, the price surged. Then (and only then) Cohen formed h=
is plan to sell. That is a stretch.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Is it? He had bought this stock, it had gone d=
own, he had a loss, he was legally required to file an updated disclosure o=
f his position that contained no new information. He filed it, the stock sh=
ot up, he was suddenly sitting on tens of millions of dollars of gains, and=
 he very sensibly said =E2=80=9Cwell this is the best chance I=E2=80=99m go=
nna get=E2=80=9D and blew out of the stock. He didn=E2=80=99t have a concre=
te plan to sell when he was sitting on a big loss, and he didn=E2=80=99t co=
ncoct a nefarious plan like =E2=80=9CI am going to file a 13D with no new i=
nformation in it, which will drive up the price, and then I=E2=80=99ll sell=
,=E2=80=9D because=C2=A0<em>that would be insane</em>. Why would re-disclos=
ing your existing stake, with no new information, cause the stock to shoot =
up? Except that it did, and he seized the moment.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Back in the olden days, I learned that securit=
ies fraud meant lying about things that would be material to a=C2=A0=E2=80=
=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32248570.290413=
/aHR0cHM6Ly9jb3JwZ292Lmxhdy5oYXJ2YXJkLmVkdS8yMDE2LzEwLzEzL3RoZS1yZWFzb25hYm=
xlLWludmVzdG9yLW9mLWZlZGVyYWwtc2VjdXJpdGllcy1sYXcv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B3bff5947" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;">reasonable investor</a>.=E2=80=9D Everyone understands t=
hat if you go around saying =E2=80=9CBed Bath has doubled sales this quarte=
r=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CBed Bath has signed an agreement to be bought by Ama=
zon at $40 per share,=E2=80=9D and you are lying, then that is fraud: You a=
re saying things that aren=E2=80=99t true and that would be material to a r=
easonable investor thinking about the stock and the company and its cash fl=
ows.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in the world of meme stocks,=C2=A0<em>ther=
e are no reasonable investors</em>. What matters is not cash flows or busin=
ess plans but memes and influencers, and so the standards for fraud are =E2=
=80=A6=C2=A0perhaps different? In the world of meme stocks, if you are a me=
me-stock influencer, and you tweet a moon emoji=C2=A0when you are in fact f=
eeling pensive-face-emoji, then arguably you are lying, and arguably your m=
isleading emoji is material to your meme-stock fans. They are not reasonabl=
e, necessarily, but they are the investors you=E2=80=99ve got, and if the s=
tock doubles due to your emoji then I guess it was material.<a class=3D"foo=
tnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !importa=
nt; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Similarly, if you accurately disclose your holding=C2=A0of a meme=
 stock, and then for boring technical reasons you have to disclose it again=
, and meme-stock investors misinterpret your new filing to mean that you ar=
e bullish, and the stock shoots up with <em>no news</em>, then they have be=
en=C2=A0<em>misled</em>, and if you didn=E2=80=99t mislead them then who di=
d? Well, they misled themselves, really. But if meme-stock investors are de=
sperate to deceive themselves, and you take advantage of their desire, mayb=
e that=E2=80=99s fraud too.</p>
