<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Barclays</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic life of a coverage investment banker=
 is that you travel around to meet with your clients and talk to them about=
 (1) what they want to do and (2) what you want them to do. So you come in,=
 you chat a bit about sports and their families, you ask =E2=80=9Cwhat=E2=
=80=99s new with you,=E2=80=9D they tell you about their business and finan=
cial concerns, and you listen intently and try to think of solutions to the=
ir problems, ideally but not necessarily solutions that involve paying your=
 bank a big fee. Then you crack open a pitchbook that your analysts prepare=
d, saying, like, =E2=80=9Chere=E2=80=99s why you should do a leveraged reca=
p=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Chere are four smaller competitors you could buy=E2=
=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cthe convertible bond market is hot and you could get gre=
at terms right now=E2=80=9D or whatever.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ideally, every so often, the client will say =
=E2=80=9Cyou know what, you=E2=80=99re right, we should buy that competitor=
, I=E2=80=99d never thought of that before but it makes total sense,=E2=80=
=9D and she will hire you to do the deal and pay you a big fee. That is par=
t of why you brought the pitchbook. But it=E2=80=99s not the only reason; y=
our hit rate will be low. Mostly you are trotting out these suggestions to =
improve your client relationship, to make your client think that you are sm=
art and have=C2=A0a lot of ideas, that you spend=C2=A0time thinking about h=
er problems and trying to find creative solutions, that you know everyone i=
n her sector and can make deals happen, and also that you have a big brain =
trust back at your bank who can execute all sorts of transactions for her. =
And then when she=C2=A0<em>does=C2=A0</em>want to do a deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
maybe one you pitched, maybe not =E2=80=94=C2=A0she will call you and give =
you a fee, because of your loyalty and creativity and hard work and deep be=
nch of subject-matter experts.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile back at the bank you=C2=A0<em>do=C2=
=A0</em>have a lot of subject-matter experts, people who make all sorts of =
financial products for banking clients, and=C2=A0<em>they=C2=A0</em>will be=
 pitching=C2=A0<em>you</em>=C2=A0on things they want you to show your clien=
ts. =E2=80=9CWe have concocted a brand-new equity derivative that your corp=
orate clients will love,=E2=80=9D the corporate-equity-derivatives people<a=
 class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpa=
rent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a> will tell you; =E2=80=9Ccan we come along=C2=A0to all your meetings th=
is month?=E2=80=9D And you will think about the pros and cons.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>Pros:</em> Maybe the client will like the =
derivative trade, do it, and pay you a big fee? Your hit rate is low, but y=
ou miss all the shots you don=E2=80=99t take. Or maybe the client will enjo=
y the derivative trade intellectually, <em>not</em> do it, but think nice t=
houghts about you because of it. Also you might as well keep the derivative=
s people happy, since you work with them, so if they want to come to some m=
eetings you might let them. Maybe they are fun to travel with.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>Cons:</em> Maybe the client will hate the =
derivative trade, be annoyed that you brought it to her, and think worse of=
 you for it. Also you get like an hour with the client, so you want to focu=
s on what you think is interesting and actionable, not what every random pr=
oduct person wants you to pitch. You have a=C2=A0<em>relationship=C2=A0</em=
>with the client; you are <em>friendly</em>; you have a running dialogue in=
 which you listen to her concerns, think about them, and come back with ide=
as to address them. =E2=80=9CHere=E2=80=99s a random derivative our guys co=
oked up=E2=80=9D might just not fit in with that story. It=C2=A0might feel =
like an annoying impersonal distraction from your friendship, an intrusion =
of=C2=A0<em>commerce=C2=A0</em>into your personal, trusted=C2=A0advisory re=
lationship.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is also I think something of a hierarchy=
 of prestige, here, among the coverage bankers. Pitching a merger? Always c=
ool. Pitching a clever bond refinancing? Sure. Pitching a weird tax trade t=
hat involves a ton of corporate restructuring, that will take your tax peop=
le 45 minutes to explain, and that no company has ever done before? Ehh, ma=
ybe, in exactly the right circumstances. Pitching =E2=80=9Cyou could save $=
25,000 a year by switching to our bank=E2=80=99s cash management product at=
 our new introductory rates=E2=80=9D? Feels like there might be more fun th=
ings you could talk about in your limited time with the client.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/32248570.290413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY=
2xlcy90cm91Ymxlcy1hdC1iYXJjbGF5cy1wcm9tcHQtYS1zaGFrZS11cGFuZC1iYW5rZXItZXhp=
dHMtYTcxYTVmOTU_bW9kPWl0cF93c2omcnU9eWFob28/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa6e5fe=
67" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> a Wall Street Journal story</a> about how Barclays Plc=E2=80=
=99s corporate and investment bank has =E2=80=9Ca strategy to become a top =
five player in as many lines of business as it can, if not investment banki=
ng overall,=E2=80=9D but has faced some struggles. It includes this complai=
nt:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The investment bank=E2=80=99s new leaders, mea=
nwhile, were internally touting the importance of diversifying how the bank=
 makes money by focusing on more =E2=80=9Csticky,=E2=80=9D recurring revenu=
es that can help balance out deal-making lulls.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Part of that goal involves becoming less relia=
nt on one of Barclays=E2=80=99s specialties, leveraged finance=E2=80=94the =
business of making high-risk loans, especially to fund mergers and acquisit=
ions=E2=80=94and earn more fees from more lucrative offerings such as helpi=
ng hedge funds execute trades and large global corporate clients manage cas=
h.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[Investment bank co-head Cathal] Deasy=E2=80=
=99s approach to making sure bankers aggressively pitch clients on the bank=
=E2=80=99s entire suite of services=E2=80=94including more closely monitori=
ng their interactions with clients=E2=80=94has rankled some, particularly t=
hose from Lehman who were accustomed to autonomy.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yes right if you are a senior investment banke=
r from Lehman who enjoys pitching clients on mergers and leveraged finance =
deals, and now you have to fill out a weekly form asking how many times you=
 have pitched Barclays=E2=80=99 cash-management services to your clients an=
d what they said, you will be rankled. Your client time is precious; you ha=
ve an hour to discuss golf and mergers, and you do not want to waste it on =
cash management, even if that happens to be a better idea=C2=A0<em>for the =
bank</em>.</p>
