<div id=3D"footnote-2" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[2] From Cohen=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32248570.290413/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYnd=
ieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3J5d2JRUlZPOUhlZy92MA/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cC60cb5887" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;">motion to dismiss</a>: =E2=80=9CPlainti=
ff=E2=80=99s Complaint, despite nearly 300 paragraphs of innuendo, hyperbol=
e, and surplusage, rests almost entirely on the implausible theory that the=
 Cohen Defendants committed securities fraud by (1) commenting on a negativ=
e article about Bed Bath &amp; Beyond, Inc. ... with a moon emoji, and (2) =
making a required filing with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission (=
=E2=80=98SEC=E2=80=99) reporting their (unchanged) holdings of BBBY shares.=
 Plaintiff contends that the Cohen Defendants intended these actions as sig=
nals to investors that BBBY=E2=80=99s stock price would increase, and that =
despite widely available information from BBBY=E2=80=99s public filings, ne=
ws articles, and market analysts that BBBY was suffering increasingly poor =
financial results, a putative class of shareholders purchased BBBY shares a=
s a result of the Cohen Defendants=E2=80=99 actions. These implausible alle=
gations do not come close to satisfying the stringent standards required to=
 plead securities fraud under Fed. R. Civ. P. 9(b) and the Private Securiti=
es Litigation Reform Act of 1995.=E2=80=9D</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-3" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[3] There is a separate legal question here, w=
hich is: Can you sue someone for general (Section 10(b)) securities fraud f=
or omissions in their 13D? =E2=80=9CNo private right of action for damages =
exists under Section 13(d),=E2=80=9D argues Cohen, and there are special ru=
les for remedies for 13D violations. Cohen argues that this means you can=
=E2=80=99t spin up a general securities-fraud claim from failure to follow =
13D rules, but the judge disagrees. I think Cohen has the better of this ar=
gument, but I am not really an expert.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-4" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[4] A technical element of securities fraud is=
 that the plaintiff has to show reliance, that is, he has to show that he w=
as deceived by the misstatements. The normal way to do that is with the "<a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32248570.290413/aHR0=
cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDctMTQvcmlwcGx=
lLWlzLWEtc2VjdXJpdHktYW5kLWl0LWlzbi10P2NtcGlkPUJCRDA3MzEyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJn=
V0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDczMSZ1d=
G1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB32122579" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">
fraud on the market</a>=E2=80=9D theory, which says that if a stock trades =
in an efficient market, it will incorporate any misstatements, and so if yo=
u bought the stock you were harmed by the misstatements. From the opinion: =
=E2=80=9CUnder the fraud-on-the-market theory, courts presume reliance when=
 a plaintiff shows =E2=80=98(1) that the alleged misrepresentations were pu=
blicly known, (2) that they were material, (3) that the stock traded in an =
efficient market, and (4) that the plaintiff traded the stock between the t=
ime the misrepresentations were made and when the truth was revealed.=E2=80=
=99=E2=80=9D That =E2=80=9Cefficient market=E2=80=9D prong is weird: =E2=80=
=9CCohen urges that Bratya has failed to allege an efficient market. As he =
explains it, =E2=80=98[i]n an efficient market, all publicly available info=
rmation is incorporated into [a company=E2=80=99s] stock price.=E2=80=99 Bu=
t here, Bed Bath=E2=80=99s stock rose after Cohen=E2=80=99s tweets and fili=
ngs, despite bleak reporting on Bed Bath=E2=80=99s outlook. Cohen says that=
 is =E2=80=98fundamentally inconsistent with . . . an efficient market.=E2=
=80=99 Cohen=E2=80=99s terse argument appears to be that the market here ca=
nnot be efficient because a stock=E2=80=99s price in an efficient market wo=
uld reflect a company=E2=80=99s fundamentals and not statements from one la=
rge investor. And =E2=80=98rational, reasonable, intelligent investors=E2=
=80=99 would not react to tweets and filings that contained no new informat=
ion.=E2=80=9D Makes sense to me! But the judge rejects that argument.</p>
</div>
